\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Exercises Week 16 - UIKit one pager
\fs28 \
\
Download the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://igor.gold.ac.uk/~mas01af/sandbox2015/week16_code.zip"}}{\fldrslt code samples}} for todays exercises.
\b0 \
\
1. Start with the page 
\i uikit_one_pager_start.html
\i0 . Lets loosen up our coding muscles by trying some basic copy and pasting to build out some content on this page. Replace the content with some of your own and do some copy/pasting to produce a page with 2-3 sections and 2-3 images. Have a look at some the core styles and try to use some of them (try breaking a paragraph into columns for example). Include a block quote or two and some subheadings to break the piece into 2-3 sections (this is so we can hook these up to a menu bar in the next sequence of exercises).  
\i From this point on you can either use your own content page by copying and pasting the code from the code samples into your own template of you can use my starting points.
\i0  \
\
2. Open the 
\i uikit_one_pager_navbar_start.html
\i0  (or copy the NAV element into your own layout), modify the code so that the menu\'92s jump to the correct sections in your page. Try adding a \'91brand\'92 to the navbar using \'91uk-navbar-brand\'92 ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AY1_hiboFg0"}}{\fldrslt help}})\
\
Fix the navigation so it jumps to the correct sections of the page by adding an css ID to the first element in each section (usually a H tag) and then put that same name into the href attribute for the relevant menu item preceded by a #. This is how to make a hyperlink to another section in the same page. Note the URL has #<id> appended to the end after you have clicked on a link that uses this technique, this means that more generally you can link a URL to a specific place on page, not just the top of the page. If you just a single # by itself with no css id in a href this will always take you to the top of the page. If you get stuck check the finished version of this page in the code samples.\
\
3. Now we want to make our menu stick to the top of the page as we scroll down. For this we use the sticky component. Note that with UIKit we get a set of features referred to as the \'91core\'92 that we will use on every page but some features are optional and grouped together as \'91components\'92, to use these we need to add a couple of extra lines of code in the header to load the specific component into the page, one for the CSS and one for the javascript. \
\
Open the file 
\i uikit_one_pager_sticky_navbar_start.html
\i0  and add the following two lines to the head section just after you have added the main CSS and Javascript for UIKit respectively. \
\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardirnatural

\f1\fs24 \cf0 <link type="text/css" rel="stylesheet" href="js/uikit-2.24.0/css/components/sticky.almost-flat.min.css" />\
<script type="text/javascript" src="js/uikit-2.24.0/js/components/sticky.min.js"></script>
\f0\fs28 \
\
Now add the following 
\i attribute
\i0  to the NAV tag and test your work.\
\

\f1\fs24 data-uk-sticky=""
\f0\fs28 \
\
Using a data-* attribute allows us to send configuration information commands to the javascript based components in UIKit such as the sticky component. The configuration commands are sent as small JSON objects we add as value to the attribute. Modify the  attribute above to read\
\

\f1\fs24 data-uk-sticky="\{clsactive: 'uk-navbar-attached'\}"
\f0\fs28 \
\
This command makes the round corners and border go away from the navbar when its stuck to the top of the page. We also tell the navbar not to appear until we have scrolled a certain amount down the page and we can also add an animation to it as it appears. Add the following two key/value pairs to the JSON configuration object you just added and test your work.\
\

\f1 top: -100, animation: 'uk-animation-slide-top'
\f0 \
\
(UIKit {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "(help%20for%20this%20exercise)"}}{\fldrslt video}} for this exercise, the only difference in my code is that I have placed the navbar outside of the central container so it goes full width)\
\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardirnatural

\i\b \cf0 Other useful options : 
\b0 On a mobile screen you might not want to navbar to stick and take up too space all the time and just let it scroll off the screen normally. The component has options for controlling this using the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://getuikit.com/docs/sticky.html#responsive-behavior"}}{\fldrslt media and orientation}} configuration options. You can also use this component in more creative ways that just a navbar, as the behaviour can be embedded inside other elements so that for example, section titles can be made to slide down over section background images and then scroll off the page with the parent element by using {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://getuikit.com/docs/sticky.html#sticky-boundary"}}{\fldrslt sticky boundaries}}.\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardirnatural

