4. The finished page from the last step (
\i uikit_one_pager_sticky_navbar_finish.html
\i0 ) has a FOOTER element in it that has a link that takes you back to the top of the page (if you have been developing your own page then just copy and paste the FOOTER element from the finished page in the code samples into your own code). When we click on this element we notice that the page jumps back to the top of the page instantly, we can improve upon this by making the page scroll visibly back to the beginning this technique is called smooth scrolling and is useful as it gives more feedback to the user about the length and type of content of the piece if the choose to skim your page before reading more. To make this happen we need to add the following attribute to the anchor tag in the footer element and test your work\
\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardirnatural

\f1\fs24 \cf0 data-uk-smooth-scroll=""
\f0\fs28 \
\
Now we want to get the menus to do the same. We could add the same attribute to each of the links but UIKit has a behaviour just for this purpose. Add the following attribute to the UL tag inside your NAV element and test your work.\
\

\f1\fs24 data-uk-scrollspy-nav="\{closest: 'li', smoothscroll: true\}"
\f0\fs28 \
\
Note that now when you click on the menu items it scrolls smoothly, also try manually scrolling down the page, you will see that the menu bar highlights the section you are in, this is a lot of functionality for not a lot of code! But there is still a problem with our UX (User eXperience!) in that when we scroll down to a section the menu bar covers the title of the section. We can fix this by passing a configuration parameter to the smooth scroll component, change the line you just added to the one below and then test your work.\
\

\f1\fs24 data-uk-scrollspy-nav="\{closest: 'li', smoothscroll: \{offset: 50\}\}
\f0\fs28 \
\
There is one feature of the default themed navbar that is a little annoying in that when we jump to a section using the navbar and then scroll into another section the both the menu item for the section we have scrolled into and the one we jumped to are both highlighted. For the default theme we need to add a bit of CSS to fix this. Add the style below below the last element inside the HEAD section.\
\

\f1\fs24 <style type="text/css">\
        .uk-navbar-nav > li:not(.uk-active) > a:active,\
        .uk-navbar-nav > li:not(.uk-active) > a:focus \{\
            background-color: inherit;\
            border-left-color: rgba(0,0,0,0);\
            border-right-color: rgba(0,0,0,0);\
        \}\
 </style>
\f0\fs28 \
\
Other UIKit themes may not have this issue, if they do then this code should work with them as well. \
\
If you get stuck then final version of this file is in the code samples folder. ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=521&v=t8Te3T8Y6EQ"}}{\fldrslt video }}help for this section)\
\
5. Open the file 
\i uikit_one_pager_mobile_start.html
\i0  and test it in a web browser. Try narrowing the screen to mobile widths, notice how the menu wraps around. We don\'92t like this, we would much rather have a hamburger menu icon like on a proper mobile site that open a menu from the side of the screen. (NB: for those who have been doing their own content this file is no different from the one in the previous step but just has more sections with longer menu items). First add this line to your your NAV element after the UL tag.\
\

\f1 <a href="#offcanvas" class="uk-navbar-toggle" data-uk-offcanvas></a>
\f0 \
\
Now add this code after the FOOTER element at the bottom of the page and test your work.\
\

\f1 <div id="offcanvas" class="uk-offcanvas">\
        <div class="uk-offcanvas-bar">\
            <li><a href="#biscuits">Proper Biscuits</a></li>\
            <li><a href="#cake">Real Cake</a></li>\
            <li><a href="#crisps">Cracking Crisps</a></li>\
        </div>\
 </div>
\f0 \
\
Clicking on the hamburger icon now opens a working mobile style navigation form the side of the screen. But when we narrow the screen to mobile widths we can still the main menus as well as the hamburger icon. Ideally we want to hide the hamburger icon when the screen is wide and then show it when the screen is narrow and at the same time hide the existing main menu. We can do this using the utility classes for showing and hiding elements depending on screen width. Have a look at the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://getuikit.com/docs/utility.html#visibility-utilities"}}{\fldrslt documentation}} in the utility classes for 
\i responsive visibility
\i0  and see if you  figure out which classes to add to which elements. If you get stuck check the finished version or look at the UIKit {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=268&v=MfdMfobt3l4"}}{\fldrslt video}} for this feature.\
\
